snippet.textDisplay:
This day was magical and hard in contrast to its title, that's why it was special probably. It really hit a weak spot on me. Made me really wonder if I was expecting too much from me, if I was trying really hard sometimes when I don't have any control on some people or situations. And made me doubt if I'm capable of soften that mental rigidity, all that I find hard every single day.
My body struggled too with this particular one, but I could accept that. I realized I couldn't accept that struggle so easily in my mind. I couldn't help crying during that final swaying plank. Surprised me because it was a weird moment but I guess I got the message. Thanks so much Adriene. Really looking forward to get home.💙💙💙

snippet.textDisplay: I am so glad I found you! Each day seems to open me up to more within myself in ways that are surprising but seem so natural. I really like how you talk about coming home. I feel like I’ve been on a journey of exploration- and in some ways I feel like I’ve gone away from myself... but I’m also aware that I really haven’t and coming home to me feels like coming home to truly who I am, without judgement and with self acceptance. And with an awareness that maybe this nagging inside is that deep, wise part of me who does want to make positive changes , keep moving forward like I do, but in healthy baby steps. Thank you!

snippet.textDisplay: Hey! I’ve actually done 5 days in a row. Super cool. I have a few basic questions. Do you have any video or resource you would point me to where I could hear some good practicals on the basics? I’m never sure if I’m positioned in the best form in downward dog for example, and I consistently have an issue figuring out how to press into the tops of my feet in tabletop or cobra. Might be a personal thing, but thought I’d ask 😂 Any tips for how you know you’re pushing yourself too far? Sometimes I feel tight afterwards and don’t know if I’m accidentally pinching things along the way. Ironic on soften day 😂🙈 Thanks for the awesome journey!

snippet.textDisplay: I have been doing yoga with Adriene every day for a month now! I have suffered lower back problems all my life, especially in the last few years and just accepted that low levels of pain and stiffness were going to be my every day reality, I've been to the physio and ostepath many times and it never really helps me long term. When I started in December, I hadn’t done any exercise for 2 years, I couldn’t even sit up straight while cross legged, I needed a tall block to sit on and I was still slouching. Today I was sitting tall and strong, without any blocks! I can do a strong plank now without the shakes, I even surprised myself with getting my feet flat on the ground for the downward dog (and not rounding my back). The back pain has slowly disappeared, today there has been no pain at all. It’s been a real breakthrough day/session today. Weirdly I think the hip opening exercises in many of the videos have really helped with that, I used to be so tight in the hips. Thanks so much Adriene, finding you has literally changed my life for good, being able to practise at home makes it so much easier to commit to regular practise which I’ve always longed for. I feel like I’ve come home to my body. xx

snippet.textDisplay:
5/30
WHY WAS THIS SO HARD FOR ME!
that was crazy! I had to stop the video and for a moment I felt so weak...my ego started telling me I couldn’t do it. I started reading the comments and some of you have beautiful stories of overcoming illness and it inspired me to keep going; to soften my doubts and to believe in myself. I was getting so frustrated because I just wanted to feeeeel into it but I couldn’t because I felt ‘off’ in my spine. When I do the extended child’s pose, on my exhale I get a sharp pain in between my shoulder blades and that’s usually a relaxing position but lately it’s been a feared one. Hopefully it gets loose soon. Anyways!! Namaste, good softening practice.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm kind of sad today because I'm getting behind. My wrists have been hurting and I don't want to push it and injure myself. So I'm going to take a break and do the yoga quickie for hands, fingers and wrists. I was already a day behind because I was really sore after day 3 and decided to take a break that day too. But this is part of my intention for this journey was not pushing myself too hard. I have had an almost daily practice for years so I felt confident I would hold myself accountable. And I'm 8 moths postpartum so I want to be careful of my healing body. I tend to push too hard instead of not hard enough. So I'm going slow, honoring my intention of being gentle. But it's also sad because I feel like a division is happening from me "not keeping up" with the pace.

snippet.textDisplay: It's been an intense two weeks with a cross-region move over Christmas, two cancer diagnoses for my in-laws, and many, many more moving parts. Yesterday was mentally very tough and I never got on my mat. I just finished this practice on day 2 of my new gig -  nannying my nearly 3 month old niece at my youngest sister's home... Thank you for the reminder to find the ease. My sweet niece is slumbering behind me in her swing, awaiting her mama to come home and nurse on her lunch break, and Meika, one of my 3 fur nieces sat peacefully beside me during my practice and kissed me on the face at namaste - life is good. I am grateful for this time ✌🏼💚🙏🏼

snippet.textDisplay: I didn't feel like doing this.  I just finished another set of 2 twelve hour night shifts that strip away at both my body and large parts of my soul. Total peace and release. I so needed this and I assume you didn't know when you made it.  So important for me.  As I got to about 20 minutes, as the transition into seated pose - the songlist I have playing in the background softly plays Jeff Buckley singing "Hallelujah".  My Higher Power is so there for me and you and your videos are such an important part of it.  Again,  thank you, thank you thank you.

snippet.textDisplay: Another thought came to me this morning. When I was 18 I had surgery on my left knee which left me with a chunk of bone below my knee, in the centre. I am working with an Athletic Therapist to strengthen and build functional mobilization in that leg but there are certain poses that are awkward because of the bump. For example, Head to Earth pose I struggle to press the top of my left foot into the earth without altering my hips. Considering the bump, what should I be focusing on when you ask us to press through the top of the foot into the earth, on the left side? Thank you for your time and energy.

snippet.textDisplay:
I did this video last night, and I know it's just day 5—but I can already sense a change in me. I actually didn't expect to notice something this soon; I've been doing regular yoga and fitness exercises for a few years now (and I love running too), so I thought doing yoga every single day wouldn't be too great an impact.


But like I said, I can already sense these changes, not just in my body, but mentally as well; I'm feeling light and positive, but also so STRONG. I'm amazed, actually, and very excited to find out how I'll be feeling once I'm halfway my yoga journey.


I just wanted to thank you, Adriene, for sharing this positive energy with all of us; you truly are one of those beautiful people who make this world a better place, and I think you're helping us all becoming better versions of ourselves as well. So—thank you!


Good luck to everyone undertaking this journey as well! I hope you all feel as great as I do now :D
